{{Year nav topic5|1632|literature}}
This article is a summary of the literary events and publications of '''1632'''.
==Events== *[[February 11]] – The Protestant pastor [[Nicolas Antoine]] is committed to an asylum after converting to Judaism. *[[February 14]] – ''[[Tempe Restored]]'', a [[masque]] written by [[Aurelian Townshend]] and designed by [[Inigo Jones]], is performed at [[Whitehall Palace]]. *March – King [[Charles I of England]] and Queen [[Henrietta Maria of France|Henrietta Maria]] visit the [[University of Cambridge]]. The students of [[Trinity College, Cambridge|Trinity College]] perform [[Thomas Randolph (poet)|Thomas Randolph]]'s ''The Jealous Lovers'' and [[Peter Hausted]]'s ''The Rival Friends''. The latter causes a theatrical riot and ensuing scandal. *May – [[Tirso de Molina]] is appointed chronicler of the [[Order of the Blessed Virgin Mary of Mercy]]. *Late – [[William Prynne]]'s ''[[Histriomastix|Histrio-mastix: The Players Scourge, or Actors Tragædie]]'', an attack on the [[English Renaissance theatre]] (dated [[1633 in literature|1633]]) is published in London. *The [[Second Folio]] of [[William Shakespeare]]'s plays is printed in London by [[Thomas Cotes]] for [[Robert Allot]] and others. Among the prefatory matter is the first published poem by [[John Milton]], printed anonymously, "An Epitaph on the Admirable Dramaticke Poet, W. Shakespeare".
==New books== ===Prose=== *[[Diego Collado]] – ''[[Diego Collado's Grammar of the Japanese Language|Ars grammaticae Iaponicae linguae]]'' *[[Phineas Fletcher]] – ''The Way to Blessedness'' and ''Joy in Tribulation'' *[[Galileo Galilei]] – ''Dialogo sopra i due massimi sistemi del mondo ([[Dialogue Concerning the Two Chief World Systems]])'' *[[Juan Pérez de Montalbán]] – ''Para todos'' *[[William Prynne]] – ''[[Histriomastix]]: the Player's Scourge, or Actor's Tragedy'' *[[Henry Reynolds (poet)|Henry Reynolds]] – ''Mythomystes''
===Drama=== *[[William Alabaster]] – ''Roxana'' ([[Latin]] play, first performed in the 1590s, published) *[[Richard Brome]] **''[[The Weeding of Covent Garden]]'' (performed) **''[[The Northern Lass]]'' (published) *[[Nathan Field]] and [[Philip Massinger]] – ''[[The Fatal Dowry]]'' (published) *[[Thomas Goffe]] – ''The Courageous Turk'' (published) *[[Thomas Heywood]] – ''The Iron Age, Part 1 and 2'' (published) *[[Ben Jonson]] – ''[[The Magnetic Lady]]'' *[[John Lyly]] – ''Six Court Comedies'' (published posthumously by [[Edward Blount]]), containing [[Campaspe (play)|''Campaspe'']], [[Endymion (play)|''Endymion'']], ''[[Gallathea]]'', [[Midas (Lyly play)|''Midas'']], ''[[Mother Bombie]]'', and ''[[Sapho and Phao]]'' *[[Jean Mairet]] – ''Les Galanteries du duc d'Ossonne'' *[[Philip Massinger]] – ''[[The City Madam]]'' (performed) **''[[The Maid of Honour]]'' published *[[Thomas Randolph (poet)|Thomas Randolph]] -''The Jealous Lovers'' **''The Muses' Looking-Glass'' *[[William Rowley (dramatist)|William Rowley]] (and others?) – ''[[A New Wonder, a Woman Never Vexed]]'' published *[[James Shirley]] **''[[The Ball (play)|The Ball]]'' **''[[Love in a Maze|The Changes, or Love in a Maze]]'' **''[[Hyde Park (play)|Hyde Park]]'' *[[John Tatham]] – ''Love Crowns the End'' *[[Aurelian Townshend]] – ''[[Tempe Restored]]'' ([[masque]])
===Poetry=== {{main|1632 in poetry}}
==Births== *[[January 1]] – [[Katherine Philips]], née Fowler, Anglo-Welsh poet, translator and woman of letters (died [[1664 in literature|1664]]) *[[January 29]] – [[Johann Georg Graevius]], German classicist (died [[1730 in literature|1730]]) *March 4 ''(baptised)'' – [[Lancelot Addison]], English author and father of [[Joseph Addison]] (died [[1703 in literature|1703]]) *[[June 10]] – [[Esprit Fléchier]], French historian and bishop (died [[1710 in literature|1710]]) *[[August 29]] – [[John Locke]], English philosopher (died [[1704 in literature|1704]]) *[[November 23]] – [[Jean Mabillon]], French palaeographer (died [[1707 in literature|1707]]) *[[November 24]] – [[Baruch Spinoza]], Dutch philosopher (died [[1677 in literature|1677]]) *[[December 17]] – [[Anthony Wood (antiquary)|Anthony Wood]], English antiquary (died [[1695 in literature|1695]]) *''Unknown date'' **[[Francis Kirkman]], English bibliophile (died c. 1680) **[[Rahman Baba]], Indian [[Pashto literature and poetry|Pashto]] poet (died [[1706 in literature|1706]])
