{{Short description|American botanical illustrator}} {{Infobox artist | name = Adelia Sarah Gates | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = October 24, 1825 | birth_place = [[Otego, New York]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1912|9|21|1825|10|24}} | death_place = [[San Francisco]], [[California]] | nationality = [[United States]] | spouse = | field = [[Botanical illustrator]] | training = Madame Vouga’s school, [[Geneva, Switzerland]] | movement = | works = | patrons = | influenced by = | influenced = | awards = | elected = | website = | bgcolour = }} '''Adelia Sarah Gates''' (October 24, 1825 - September 21, 1912) was an American [[botanical illustrator|illustrator]] of botanical specimens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Record Unit 7312|work=Adelia Gates Collection|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Archives|url=http://siarchives.si.edu/collections/siris_arc_217469}}</ref><ref>[http://www.askart.com/askart/artist.aspx?artist=11176149 Adelia Sarah Gates, AskArt]</ref> Her early work was as an elementary teacher and decorative watercolorist.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lockshin|first=Nora|title=Adelia Gates—Flower Painter or Botanical Illustrator?|url=http://siarchives.si.edu/blog/adelia-gates-flower-painter-or-botanical-illustrator|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Archives}}</ref><ref name="Orpen1897">{{cite book|author=Adela Elizabeth Richards Orpen|title=The chronicles of the Sid: or, The life and travels of Adelia Gates|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQso6C_jJLAC|accessdate=30 March 2012|year=1897|publisher=Ayer Publishing|isbn=978-0-8369-9145-1|page=27}}</ref> She was an amateur decorative watercolorist and painter long before she was able to advance further into scientific illustration methods and to travel widely on collecting and documentation expeditions later in her life.
She was born in the [[Susquehanna Valley]].<ref name=SIA>{{cite web|title=Adelia Gates Collection, 1879-1898 and undated|url=http://siarchives.si.edu/collections/siris_arc_217469|work=SIA RU007312|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution Archives]]|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref> Gates worked as a guardian, farmworker, teacher, and as a [[Lowell Mill Girls|factory worker in the Lowell Mills]] before being attending college.<ref>{{cite book|last=Orpen|first=Adela Elizabeth Richards|title=The chronicles of the Sid: or, The life and travels of Adelia Gates|year=1897|publisher=Fleming H. Revell Company|location=New York, Chicago}}</ref> In her thirties, she attended [[Antioch College]], only to leave after two years due to health issues. She started painting in her fifties, after taking lessons from [[Emilie Vouga]] in Geneva.<ref name=SIA/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Vouga, Emilie|year=2011|doi=10.1093/benz/9780199773787.article.B00192924}}</ref>
During her lifetime, a colorful biography of her life and travels was written by [[Adela Orpen|Adela Elizabeth Orpen]], published by the [[Religious Tract Society]]. After her death, over 600 of her works were exhibited and donated to the [[United States National Museum]], which later became the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>"Learned to paint at 50". ''The Washington Post'' 27 Apr 1914</ref>
