{{Infobox person | name = Mia Schaikewitz | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth-date and age|May 23, 1978}} | height = {{height|m=1.778}} | birth_place = Atlanta, Georgia USA | education = [[University of Florida]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | other_names = | notable works = [[Push Girls]] }}
'''Mia Schaikewitz''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ʃ|aɪ|k|ᵻ|w|ɪ|t|s}}; born May 23, 1978) is a Jewish-American<ref>{{cite journal|last=Carlson|first=Laurie Ann|title=Wired for Interdependency: ''Push Girls'' and cyborg sexuality|journal=Feminist Media Studies|date=August 23, 2013|volume=13|issue=4|pages=754–759|doi=10.1080/14680777.2013.805591|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/14680777.2013.805591|accessdate=4 April 2014}}</ref> TV personality and spokesperson for disability advocacy. She stars in the reality series ''[[Push Girls]]'' on the [[SundanceTV|Sundance Channel]].
==Early life and career== A competitive swimmer at the time, Schaikewitz became paralyzed from the waist down "over the course of a half-day"<ref>{{cite episode |title=Everyone Stares |episodelink=Push_Girls#Season_1_.282012.29 |series=Push Girls |serieslink=Push Girls |network=Sundance Channel |date=June 4, 2012 |season=1 |number=1 |quote=paralyzed me from the waist down over the course of a half-day}}</ref> after an [[arteriovenous malformation]] (AVM) ruptured in her spinal cord when she was 15.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/women-in-wheelchairs-push-boundaries-in-real-life-and-on-tv |first=Naomi |last=Pfefferman | title=Women in wheelchairs push boundaries in real life and on TV | publisher=[[The Times of Israel]] | date=June 11, 2012 |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mia-schaikewitz |title=Mia Schaikewitz |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=July 3, 2012 |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> She went on to graduate with a degree from the [[University of Florida]] and then moved to [[Los Angeles]] where she developed a career in graphic design and branding.<ref name="ABILITY Magazine">{{Cite journal|title=Push Girls&nbsp;— Living Large|url=http://www.abilitymagazine.com/Push-Girls-Interview.html|publisher=ABILITY Magazine|accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundancechannel.com/series/push-girls/cast/mia-schaikewitz |title=Push Girls - Mia Schaikewitz |publisher=SundanceTV |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> In 2012, she decided to return to the sport of competitive swimming after 17 years, as documented in Season 1 of the show ''[[Push Girls]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2012/06/13/154938487 | title='Push Girls' Wheel Chairs Through Life And Love | series=[[Talk of the Nation]] | publisher=[[National Public Radio]] | date=June 13, 2012 |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>
==Awards and nominations== * In 2013, ''Push Girls'' won the Critics' Choice Best Reality Series award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lamag.com/laculture/culturefilesblog/2013/06/11/push-girls-win-big-at-critics-choice-awards|title=Push Girls Win Big at Critic's Choice Awards|publisher=www.LAmag.com|author=Andrea Alonso|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref>
